"<literal>autoyast=<replaceable>URL</replaceable></literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11228
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>autoyast2=<replaceable>URL</replaceable></literal> is not "
"supported, because this option downloads a single &ay; control file only."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11235
#, no-c-format
msgid "Rule-based Automatic Installation"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11237
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Rules offer the possibility to configure a system depending on system "
"attributes by merging multiple control files during installation. The rules-"
"based installation is controlled by a rules file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11242
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, this could be useful to install systems in two departments in "
"one go. Assume a scenario where machines in department A need to be "
"installed as office desktops, whereas machines in department B need to be "
"installed as developer workstations. You would create a rules file with two "
"different rules. For each rule, you could use different system parameters to "
"distinguish the installations from one another. Each rule would also contain "
"a link to an appropriate profile for each department."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11253
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The rules file is an XML file containing rules for each group of systems (or "
"single systems) that you want to automatically install. A set of rules "
"distinguish a group of systems based on one or more system attributes. After "
"passing all rules, each group of systems is linked to a control file. Both "
"the rules file and the control files must be located in a pre-defined and "
"accessible location."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11262
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The rules file is retrieved only if no specific control file is supplied "
"using the <literal>autoyast</literal> keyword. For example, if the following "
"is used, the rules file will not be evaluated:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11268
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"autoyast=http://10.10.0.1/profile/myprofile.xml\n"
"autoyast=http://10.10.0.1/profile/rules/rules.xml"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11270
#, no-c-format
msgid "Instead use:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11274
#, no-c-format
msgid "autoyast=http://10.10.0.1/profile/"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11276
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"which will load <literal>http://10.10.0.1/profile/rules/rules.xml</literal> "
"(the slash at the end of the directory name is important)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11283
#, no-c-format
msgid "Rules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11294
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If more than one rule applies, the final control file for each group is "
"generated on the fly using a merge script. The merging process is based on "
"the order of the rules and later rules override configuration data in "
"earlier rules. Note that the names of the top sections in the merged xml "
"files need to be in alphabetical order for the merge to succeed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11302
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The use of a rules file is optional. If the rules file is not found, system "
"installation proceeds in the standard way by using the supplied control file "
"or by searching for the control file depending on the MAC or the IP address "
"of the system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11310
#, no-c-format
msgid "Rules File Explained"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11312 ay_bigfile.xml:11347
#, no-c-format
msgid "Simple Rules File"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11313
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following simple example illustrates how the rules file is used to "
"retrieve the configuration for a client with known hardware."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11317
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\"?&gt;\n"
"&lt;!DOCTYPE autoinstall&gt;\n"
"&lt;autoinstall xmlns=\"http://www.suse.com/1.0/yast2ns\" xmlns:config="
"\"http://www.suse.com/1.0/configns\"&gt;\n"
"  &lt;rules config:type=\"list\"&gt;\n"
"    &lt;rule&gt;\n"
"       &lt;disksize&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match&gt;/dev/sdc 1000&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match_type&gt;greater&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"       &lt;/disksize&gt;\n"
"       &lt;result&gt;\n"
"            &lt;profile&gt;department_a.xml&lt;/profile&gt;\n"
"            &lt;continue config:type=\"boolean\"&gt;false&lt;/continue&gt;\n"
"        &lt;/result&gt;\n"
"    &lt;/rule&gt;\n"
"    &lt;rule&gt;\n"
"       &lt;disksize&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match&gt;/dev/sda 1000&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match_type&gt;greater&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"       &lt;/disksize&gt;\n"
"       &lt;result&gt;\n"
"            &lt;profile&gt;department_b.xml&lt;/profile&gt;\n"
"            &lt;continue config:type=\"boolean\"&gt;false&lt;/continue&gt;\n"
"        &lt;/result&gt;\n"
"    &lt;/rule&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/rules&gt;\n"
"&lt;/autoinstall&gt;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11319
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The last example defines two rules and provides a different control file for "
"every rule. The rule used in this case is <literal>disksize</literal>. After "
"parsing the rules file, &yast; attempts to match the target system with the "
"rules in the <filename>rules.xml</filename> file. A rule match occurs when "
"the target system matches all system attributes defined in the rule. When "
"the system matches a rule, the respective resource is added to the stack of "
"control files &ay; will use to create the final control file. The "
"<literal>continue</literal> property tells &ay; whether it should continue "
"with other rules after a match has been found."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11330
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the first rule does not match, the next rule in the list is examined "
"until a match is found."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11334
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using the <literal>disksize</literal> attribute, you can provide different "
"configurations for systems with hard disks of different sizes. The first "
"rule checks if the device <filename>/dev/sdc</filename> is available and if "
"it is greater than 1 GB in size using the <literal>match</literal> property."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11341
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A rule must have at least one attribute to be matched. If you need to check "
"more attributes, such as memory or architectures, you can add more "
"attributes in the rule resource as shown in the next example."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11348
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following example illustrates how the rules file is used to retrieve the "
"configuration for a client with known hardware."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11352
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&lt;?xml version=\"1.0\"?&gt;\n"
"&lt;!DOCTYPE autoinstall&gt;\n"
"&lt;autoinstall xmlns=\"http://www.suse.com/1.0/yast2ns\" xmlns:config="
"\"http://www.suse.com/1.0/configns\"&gt;\n"
"  &lt;rules config:type=\"list\"&gt;\n"
"    &lt;rule&gt;\n"
"       &lt;disksize&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match&gt;/dev/sdc 1000&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match_type&gt;greater&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"       &lt;/disksize&gt;\n"
"       &lt;memsize&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match&gt;1000&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match_type&gt;greater&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"       &lt;/memsize&gt;\n"
"       &lt;result&gt;\n"
"            &lt;profile&gt;department_a.xml&lt;/profile&gt;\n"
"            &lt;continue config:type=\"boolean\"&gt;false&lt;/continue&gt;\n"
"        &lt;/result&gt;\n"
"    &lt;/rule&gt;\n"
"    &lt;rule&gt;\n"
"       &lt;disksize&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match&gt;/dev/shda 1000&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match_type&gt;greater&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"       &lt;/disksize&gt;\n"
"       &lt;memsize&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match&gt;256&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"            &lt;match_type&gt;greater&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"       &lt;/memsize&gt;\n"
"       &lt;result&gt;\n"
"            &lt;profile&gt;department_b.xml&lt;/profile&gt;\n"
"            &lt;continue config:type=\"boolean\"&gt;false&lt;/continue&gt;\n"
"        &lt;/result&gt;\n"
"    &lt;/rule&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/rules&gt;\n"
"&lt;/autoinstall&gt;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11354
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The rules directory must be located in the same directory specified via the "
"<literal>autoyast</literal> keyword at boot time. If the client was booted "
"using <literal>autoyast=http://10.10.0.1/profiles/</literal>, &ay; will "
"search for the rules file at http://10.10.0.1/profiles/rules/rules.xml."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11364
#, no-c-format
msgid "Custom Rules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11365
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the attributes &ay; provides for rules are not enough for your purposes, "
"use custom rules. Custom rules contain a shell script. The output of the "
"script (STDOUT, STDERR is ignored) can be evaluated."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11370
#, no-c-format
msgid "Here is an example for the use of custom rules:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11373
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&lt;rule&gt;\n"
"  &lt;custom1&gt;\n"
"    &lt;script&gt;\n"
"if grep -i intel /proc/cpuinfo &gt; /dev/null; then\n"
"echo -n \"intel\"\n"
"else\n"
"echo -n \"non_intel\"\n"
"fi;\n"
"    &lt;/script&gt;\n"
"    &lt;match&gt;*&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"    &lt;match_type&gt;exact&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/custom1&gt;\n"
"  &lt;result&gt;\n"
"    &lt;profile&gt;@custom1@.xml&lt;/profile&gt;\n"
"    &lt;continue config:type=\"boolean\"&gt;true&lt;/continue&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/result&gt;\n"
"&lt;/rule&gt;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11374
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The script in this rule can echo either <literal>intel</literal> or "
"<literal>non_intel</literal> to STDOUT (the output of the grep command must "
"be directed to /dev/null in this case). The output of the rule script will "
"be filled between the two '@' characters, to determine the file name of the "
"control file to fetch. &ay; will read the output and fetch a file with the "
"name <filename>intel.xml</filename> or <filename>non_intel.xml</filename>. "
"This file can contain the &ay; profile part for the software selection; for "
"example, in case you want a different software selection on intel hardware "
"than on others."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11385
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The number of custom rules is limited to five. So you can use "
"<literal>custom1</literal> to <literal>custom5</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11392
#, no-c-format
msgid "Match Types for Rules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11393
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can use five different match_types:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11398
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>exact</literal> (default)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11404
#, no-c-format
msgid "greater"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11409
#, no-c-format
msgid "lower"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11414
#, no-c-format
msgid "range"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11418
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>regex</literal> (a simple <literal>=~</literal> operator like in "
"Bash)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11424
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If using <literal>exact</literal>, the string must match exactly as "
"specified. <literal>regex</literal> can be used to match substrings like "
"<literal>ntel</literal> will match Intel, intel and intelligent. "
"<literal>greater</literal> and <literal>lower</literal> can be used for "
"<literal>memsize</literal> or <literal>totaldisk</literal> for example. They "
"can match only with rules that return an integer value. A range is only "
"possible for integer values too and has the form of <literal>value1-value2</"
"literal>, for example <literal>512-1024</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11437
#, no-c-format
msgid "Combine Attributes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11438
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Multiple attributes can be combined via a logical operator. It is possible "
"to let a rule match if <literal>disksize</literal> is greater than 1GB or "
"<literal>memsize</literal> is exactly 512MB."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11443
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can do this with the <literal>operator</literal> element in the rules."
"xml file. <literal>and</literal> and <literal>or</literal> are possible "
"operators, <literal>and</literal> being the default. Here is an example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11449
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&lt;rule&gt;\n"
"  &lt;disksize&gt;\n"
"    &lt;match&gt;/dev/sda 1000&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"    &lt;match_type&gt;greater&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/disksize&gt;\n"
"  &lt;memsize&gt;\n"
"    &lt;match&gt;256&lt;/match&gt;\n"
"    &lt;match_type&gt;greater&lt;/match_type&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/memsize&gt;\n"
"  &lt;result&gt;\n"
"    &lt;profile&gt;machine2.xml&lt;/profile&gt;\n"
"    &lt;continue config:type=\"boolean\"&gt;false&lt;/continue&gt;\n"
"  &lt;/result&gt;\n"
"  &lt;operator&gt;or&lt;/operator&gt;\n"
"&lt;/rule&gt;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11453
#, no-c-format
msgid "Rules File Structure"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11454
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <filename>rules.xml</filename> file needs to:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: ay_bigfile.xml:11459
